# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-monitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] An **alarm device** is a mechanism that gives an audible, visual, combination, or other kind of alarm signal to alert someone to a problem or condition that requires urgent attention.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] The word *alarm* comes from the Old French *a l'arme* meaning "to the arms", or "to the weapons", telling armed men to pick up their weapons and get ready for action because an enemy may have suddenly appeared.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] The word *alarum* is an archaic form of *alarm*.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] It was sometimes used as a call to arms in the stage directions of Elizabethan dramas.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] The term comes from the Italian *all'armi* and appears 89 times in Shakespeare's First Folio.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Often explained as the off-stage sounds of conflict or disturbance, recent research suggests a bell or drum may have been used to rouse soldiers from sleep.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Early alarm devices were often bells, drums, other musical instruments, or any items which made unusual loud noises that attracted the attention of the surrounding population.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Whistles were used by police in the 19th century.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Steam whistles have been used on locomotives, ships, and in factories as alarm devices.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] With the advent of electricity, a variety of other alerting devices have been invented, such as buzzers, klaxons, sirens, horns, flashing and coloured lights, and other all-purpose alarms.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Alarm devices can be fitted to buildings as well as vehicles.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Many buildings are fitted with fire alarms, ranging from a self-contained domestic smoke detector to a sophisticated alarm system that can operate building fire fighting systems automatically to extinguish fires with water or inert gases.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Many industries have developed standards for alarm devices, and the colours red, blue and amber are generally recognized as alarm device-related colours, with flashing lights often indicating urgent conditions.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Human reactions to an alarm will often depend on upbringing, psychological training, or the behavior of others in the environment.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Consequently, the ability to test an alarm and hold regular drills to practice an appropriate response may be provided as part of an alarm system.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Alarm devices that are intended to cause the evacuation of an occupied building, such as fire alarms, may be deliberately designed to make remaining in the space difficult or even painful in order to encourage occupants to leave.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Some alarms may startle and cause a fight-or-flight response in humans; a person under this mindset will panic and either flee the perceived danger or attempt to eliminate it, often ignoring rational thought in either case.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] A person in such a state can be characterized as "alarmed".
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] With any kind of alarm, people must balance between the danger of false alarms (called "false positives") — the signal going off in the absence of a problem — or an alarm failing to signal an actual problem (called a "false negative").
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] False alarms can waste resources expensively and can even be dangerous.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] For example, false alarms of a fire can waste firefighter manpower, making them unavailable for a real fire, and risk injury to firefighters and others as the fire engines race to the alleged fire's location.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] In addition, false alarms may acclimatise people to ignore alarm signals, and thus possibly to ignore an actual emergency: Aesop's fable of *The Boy Who Cried Wolf* exemplifies this problem.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] A false alarm is one of the most significant issues with conventional alarm systems.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] They can be triggered for several reasons, such as the movement of pets, typing in the wrong security codes, or loud sounds from windows or doors.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] In the case of fire alarms, aerosol sprays, smoking, or burning food can all lead to a false alarm.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] Many avoid the risk of false alarms by ensuring their alarms are secured in an appropriate location, such as placing a smoke detector or fire alarm away from the kitchen where smoke from burned food or large quantities of steam which may trigger a false alarm are common occurrences.
[src:azure-monitor/alarm-device] In the case of a security alarm, an additional monitoring station which assesses whether there is a legitimate need for help can reduce false alarms.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:azure-monitor/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] While an intrusion detection system monitors network threats from the outside, a network monitoring system monitors the network for problems caused by overloaded or crashed servers, network connections or other devices.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] For example, to determine the status of a web server, monitoring software may periodically send an HTTP request to fetch a page.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] For email servers, a test message might be sent through SMTP and retrieved by IMAP or POP3.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Commonly measured metrics are response time, availability and uptime, although both consistency and reliability metrics are starting to gain popularity.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] The widespread addition of WAN optimization devices is having an adverse effect on most network monitoring tools, especially when it comes to measuring accurate end-to-end delay because they limit round-trip delay time visibility.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Status request failures, such as when a connection cannot be established, it times-out, or the document or message cannot be retrieved, usually produce an action from the monitoring system.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] These actions vary; An alarm may be sent (via SMS, email, etc.) to the resident sysadmin, automatic failover systems may be activated to remove the troubled server from duty until it can be repaired, etc.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Monitoring the performance of a network uplink is also known as network traffic measurement.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Network tomography is an important area of network measurement, which deals with monitoring the health of various links in a network using end-to-end probes sent by agents located at vantage points in the network/Internet.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Route analytics is another important area of network measurement.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] It includes the methods, systems, algorithms and tools to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation or downtime.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Site monitoring services can check HTTP pages, HTTPS, SNMP, FTP, SMTP, POP3, IMAP, DNS, SSH, TELNET, SSL, TCP, ICMP, SIP, UDP, Media Streaming and a range of other ports with a variety of check intervals ranging from every four hours to every one minute.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Typically, most network monitoring services test your server anywhere between once per hour to once per minute.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] For monitoring network performance, most tools use protocols like SNMP, NetFlow, Packet Sniffing, or WMI.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Monitoring an internet server means that the server owner always knows if one or all of their services go down.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Server monitoring may be **internal**, i.e. web server software checks its status and notifies the owner if some services go down, and **external**, i.e. some web server monitoring companies check the status of the services with a certain frequency.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Server monitoring can encompass a check of system metrics, such as CPU usage, memory usage, network performance and disk space.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] It can also include application monitoring, such as checking the processes of programs such as Apache HTTP server, MySQL, Nginx, Postgres and others.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] External monitoring is more reliable, as it keeps on working when the server completely goes down.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Good server monitoring tools also have performance benchmarking, alerting capabilities and the ability to link certain thresholds with automated server jobs, such as provisioning more memory or performing a backup.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Network monitoring services usually have several servers around the globe - for example in America, Europe, Asia, Australia and other locations.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] By having multiple servers in different geographic locations, a monitoring service can determine if a Web server is available across different networks worldwide.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] The more the locations used, the more complete the picture of network availability.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] When monitoring a web server for potential problems, an external web monitoring service checks several parameters.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] First of all, it monitors for a proper HTTP return code.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] By HTTP specifications RFC 2616, any web server returns several HTTP codes.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Analysis of the HTTP codes is the fastest way to determine the current status of the monitored web server.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Third-party application performance monitoring tools provide additional web server monitoring, alerting and reporting capabilities.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] As the information brought by web server monitoring services is in most cases urgent and may be of crucial importance, various notification methods may be used: e-mail, landline and cell phones, messengers, SMS, fax, pagers, etc.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] Network monitoring plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements across multiple industries.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would mandate continuous monitoring of all information systems containing ePHI, including deployment of technology assets that can detect and respond to threats in real time.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires organizations to track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data (Requirement 10), including the use of network monitoring tools to detect unauthorized wireless access points.
[src:azure-monitor/network-monitoring] For U.S. federal agencies, NIST Special Publication 800-53 mandates continuous monitoring under the CA-7 control family as part of the Risk Management Framework.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:azure-monitor/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] A **system monitor** is a hardware or software component used to monitor system resources and performance in a computer system.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Among the management issues regarding use of system monitoring tools are resource usage and privacy.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Monitoring can track both input and output values and events of systems.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Software monitors occur more commonly, sometimes as a part of a widget engine.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] These monitoring systems are often used to keep track of system resources, such as CPU usage and frequency, or the amount of free RAM.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] They are also used to display items such as free space on one or more hard drives, the temperature of the CPU and other important components, and networking information including the system IP address and current rates of upload and download.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Other possible displays may include the date and time, system uptime, computer name, username, hard drive S.M.A.R.T. data, fan speeds, and the voltages being provided by the power supply.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Less common are hardware-based systems monitoring similar information.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Customarily these occupy one or more drive bays on the front of the computer case, and either interface directly with the system hardware or connect to a software data-collection system via USB.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] With either approach to gathering data, the monitoring system displays information on a small LCD panel or on series of small analog or LED numeric displays.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Some hardware-based system monitors also allow direct control of fan speeds, allowing the user to quickly customize the cooling in the system.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] The primary function of a few very high-end models of hardware system monitor is to interface with only a specific model of motherboard.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] These systems directly utilize the sensors built into the system, providing more detailed and accurate information than less-expensive monitoring systems customarily provide.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Software monitoring tools operate within the device they're monitoring.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Unlike software monitoring tools, hardware measurement tools can either located within the device being measure, or they can be attached and operate from an external location.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] A **hardware monitor** is a common component of modern motherboards, which can either come as a separate chip, often interfaced through I2C or SMBus, or as part of a Super I/O solution, often interfaced through Low Pin Count (LPC).
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] These devices make it possible to monitor temperature in the chassis, voltage supplied to the motherboard by the power supply unit and the speed of the computer fans that are connected directly to one of the fan headers on the motherboard.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Many of these hardware monitors also have fan controlling capabilities.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] System monitoring software like SpeedFan on Windows, lm_sensors on Linux, envstat on NetBSD, and sysctl hw.sensors on OpenBSD and DragonFly can interface with these chips to relay this environmental sensor information to the user.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] When an individual user is measuring the performance of a single-user system, whether it is a standalone box or a virtual machine on a multi-user system, access does not impede the privacy of others.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Privacy becomes an issue when someone other than the end-user, such as a system manager, has legitimate need to access data about other users.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] When events occur faster than a monitor can record them, a workaround is needed, such as replacing event recording with simple counting.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] Another consideration is not having major impact on the CPU and storage available for useful work.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] While a hardware monitor will usually have less impact than a software monitor, there are data items, such as "some descriptive information, such as program names" that must involve software.
[src:azure-monitor/system-monitor] A further consideration is that a bug in this domain can have severe impact: an extreme case would "cause the OS to crash".
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:azure-monitor/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
